div.div:
A version must remain separate iff there exists any transaction whose snapshot does not cover the version.
Reason: Each transaction must check for conflicts; hence the boundary between <its snapshot> and <the version immediately older than the snapshot> must not be erased.
As a transaction performs conflict checks, it expands its snapshot to include the newest version at that time, and registers a change of its required minimum separate version.
A multiset tracks required separate versions.

div.div:
Bad.
Pretext 1: A missing commit_ver is perfectly normal. Reason: For each secondary index, each commit is a delta. If a commit version did not affect the secondary index, that commit version is not represented in that secondary index. However, if we are to wastefully persist all commit versions even if empty, then there is no gap.
Pretext 2: When a transaction traverses over a specified range of commit_vers, it might detect missing commit_vers. Even so, it's not clear how it should wait till those missing versions become available. Reading is lockless, so spin-wait would likely be the solution. Hence, we decide that transactions should ignore and not remember missing commit_vers.
Anomaly e.g.:
Transaction sees P=x+1, and defines its initial snapshot as ( -inf ... x+1 ]. It traverses the list but does not encounter node with commit_ver=x+1.
Transaction sees P = x' > x+1; expands its snapshot; and reads within [ x+2 ... x' ]. It does not attempt to read node with commit_ver=x+1. This node is never read.

div.div:
Linked list design considerations
Operations on the linked list are:
By transactions
Get one key-value entry => Read newer-to-older.
Get range of key-value entries => Read in either direction. (Then, k-merge a slice.)
Check conflicts => Read a slice close to the newest end, in either direction.
Commit => Push a node at the newest end.
By the flushing+compacting job
Read in either direction
Replace a slice with a node, anywhere in the list
By secondary index creation job
Push a slice at the oldest endWho should flush: transactions or the job?
If transactions flush:
Flush before or after conflict-checks?
Before would worsen the probability of the flushed SSTable to be discarded, never to be read.
After would worsen the duration of the committing operation. Committing should be mutually excluded. This gets worse as the number of secondary indexes increases.
Transaction could flush + compact at its own schedule. It would hold its written data in an LSMTree and runs GC at configurable thresholds.
If the job flushes:
Flushing and/or compacting MemLogs should be prioritized over compacting SSTables, to minimize memory footprint.Singly-linked vs doubly-linked:
We clearly need newer-to-older traversal.
Adding older-to-newer traversal could benefit the job.
The selection of slices to flush and/or compact can be designed more flexibly.
Doubly-linked helps us experiment with various slice selection (prioritization) approaches.
In case the job is responsible for flushing, older-to-newer traversal makes it easier to guarantee a single boundary across which all older nodes are SSTables and all newer nodes are MemLogs.
One side-benefit from this is that k-merging is easier to impl with a simpler type system (we need one k-merged iterator for SSTables and one ditto for SSTables); but it's possible to work around this, so this is low-priority.
MemLog --> Iterator< Item = (&K, &OptDatum<V>) >
SSTable --> Iterator< Item = Result<(K, OptDatum<V>)> >
See a separate architecture diagram for an analysis on concurrency.
The simplest solution for doubly-linked design seems to be to mutually exclude pushing and replacing.
In the actual impl, pushing a new commit is followed by bumping next_commit_ver under lock; and replacing a slice is followed by bumping curr_list_ver under lock. Unfortunately, these are different locks; hence either transactions or the job must acquire a lock that is unrelated to its logic or data.
In conclusion, go with "singly-linked design #2".In summary, the current chosen design is:
Singly-linked.
The job flushes.
Operations insert dummies in order to create a slice within which there is no contention for modification.
The only contention is for pushing a node as the newest.

div.div:
If we were to derive SI by converting from PI node-by-node, then for each (PK, PV) entry, we would need to look up the previous (PK, PV) that was overwritten. This would be very inefficient. Instead, we k-merge the entire PI and process only the newest-version PV for each PK.
The SI creation job is responsible for this k-merging; future commits are responsible for incremental, version-by-version deltas.
1. Remember the current next_commit_ver as the exclusive upper bound of versions for which the SI creation job is responsible (We'll call this job_ver_ceil).
2. The SI creator job k-merges the PI in versions older than job_ver_ceil, and builds one or more SSTables. While the job runs, newer versions will be pushed by transactions.
3. Wait till job_ver_ceil <= min separate commit ver.
4. Mark the SI as readable by transactions.

1. Remember the current next_commit_ver as the snapshot's exclusive upper bound.
2. Execute RMW operations. Reading is from within the snapshot range, in any index that's accessed. Writing is to a transaction-local MemLog (or in the future, potentially a transaction-local LSMTree).
2a. Writing also needs to read the (PK, PV) entries that this transaction will replace. These old entries are required when building the commit for each secondary index.
3. Check conflicts between snapshot's upper bound and the current next_commit_ver. Repeat while (actual next_commit_ver != last known next_commit_ver).
4. Push to all indexes, including work-in-progress secondary indexes whose older data have not yet been built.
